Note:
==============================================================================
FIELD448 - Arithmetic in F_p with p = 2^448 - 2^224 - 1 (Goldilocks)
==============================================================================

Foundation for Ed448 (untwisted Edwards curve "edwards448") and X448
(Montgomery curve "curve448"). All field operations are constant-time.

Representation: 16 limbs of radix 2^28. Each limb holds bits
[28*i, 28*(i+1)) of the 448-bit field value as a 64-bit signed integer.
A field element occupies FIELD448_BYTES = 128 bytes.

The Goldilocks prime p = phi^2 - phi - 1 where phi = 2^224 admits an
elegant reduction: 2^448 = 2^224 + 1 (mod p). So in the 16-limb
representation, a product limb at position 16+i contributes both to
limb i (the +1 part) and to limb i+8 (the +2^224 part, since each limb
spans 28 bits and 224 / 28 = 8).

Reference:
- M. Hamburg, "Ed448-Goldilocks, a new elliptic curve", 2015.
- RFC 7748 sections 4.2, 5 (X448).
- RFC 8032 section 5.2 (Ed448).
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "runtime/core/memory/arena.runa" as Arena

Constant FIELD448_BYTES as Integer is 128
Constant FIELD448_MASK28 as Integer is 268435455
Constant FIELD448_TWO_TO_28 as Integer is 268435456

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 1: Allocation and element setup
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe448_alloc" takes arena as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Allocates a 128-byte buffer for a 16-limb radix-2^28 field element.
    Zero-initializes all limbs.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Arena-backed; lifetime tied to arena.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let buffer be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, FIELD448_BYTES)
    If buffer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Memory.memory_set_qword(buffer, i multiplied by 8, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return buffer
End Process

Process called "fe448_set_zero" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, i multiplied by 8, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe448_set_one" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 0, 1)
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 16:
        Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, i multiplied by 8, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe448_copy" takes dest as Integer, src as Integer returns Integer:
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let li be Memory.memory_get_int64(src, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, li)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 2: Add, Sub, Neg
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe448_add" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Component-wise addition. Each limb sum stays well within 64-bit
    range as long as |a_i|, |b_i| < 2^62 (which holds before any
    reduction-bounded multiplications).
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: 16 unconditional add/store ops.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Let bi be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, ai plus bi)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe448_sub" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Let bi be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, ai minus bi)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe448_neg" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, 0 minus ai)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 3: Carry propagation through 16 limbs + Goldilocks reduction wrap
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe448_carry" takes h as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Propagates carries through all 16 limbs and normalizes each limb
    into [0, 2^28). The overflow from limb 15 (top, 28-bit) wraps via
    the Goldilocks identity 2^448 = 2^224 + 1, which in our
    representation means:
      - carry_out_15 contributes to limb 0 (the "+1" part)
      - carry_out_15 contributes to limb 8 (the "+2^224" part)

    The "balanced carry" pattern `c = (hi + 2^27) >> 28; hi -= c * 2^28`
    leaves the residual limb in the signed range [-2^27, 2^27). A
    force-positive pass after the standard carries adds 2^28 to any
    negative limb and propagates a -1 borrow to the next-higher limb,
    bringing every limb into [0, 2^28). If a final borrow remains at
    limb 15, the field value went < 0 and we added 2^448; since
    2^448 = 2^224 + 1 (mod p), we compensate by subtracting 1 from
    limb 0 and 1 from limb 8. A final cleanup pass absorbs any
    transient negative limbs introduced by that compensation.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Three stages:
      1. Balanced carry chain 0..15 plus wrap-back of limb-15 overflow
         into limbs 0 and 8, followed by a second balanced carry pass
         over limbs 0..8 to absorb the wrap.
      2. Force-positive linear sweep 0..15 turning every signed limb
         non-negative via borrow propagation. A final borrow out of
         limb 15 triggers a -1 adjustment to limbs 0 and 8 per the
         Goldilocks reduction identity.
      3. A second force-positive sweep over limbs 0..8 catches any
         negative residue introduced when limbs 0 and 8 received the
         -1 borrow compensation, ensuring all limbs end in [0, 2^28)
         when callers expect normalized output.
    @End Implementation

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: every conditional is a sign-driven mask/borrow that
    executes the same instruction sequence regardless of limb value.
    The implementation uses (limb shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    style sign extraction with no data-dependent branching.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 15:
        Let hi be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, i multiplied by 8)
        Let c_pre be hi plus 134217728
        Let c be c_pre shifted right by 28
        Let c_lo be c multiplied by 268435456
        Set hi to hi minus c_lo
        Memory.memory_set_qword(h, i multiplied by 8, hi)
        Let h_next be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, (i plus 1) multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(h, (i plus 1) multiplied by 8, h_next plus c)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Wrap limb 15 -> limb 0 (+1) and limb 8 (+1 from 2^224 path).
    Let h15 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 120)
    Let c15_pre be h15 plus 134217728
    Let c15 be c15_pre shifted right by 28
    Let c15_lo be c15 multiplied by 268435456
    Set h15 to h15 minus c15_lo
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 120, h15)

    Let h0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 0)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 0, h0 plus c15)
    Let h8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 64)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 64, h8 plus c15)

    Note: Second carry pass over limbs 0..8 to absorb the wrap.
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than 9:
        Let hi2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, j multiplied by 8)
        Let c_pre2 be hi2 plus 134217728
        Let c2 be c_pre2 shifted right by 28
        Let c_lo2 be c2 multiplied by 268435456
        Set hi2 to hi2 minus c_lo2
        Memory.memory_set_qword(h, j multiplied by 8, hi2)
        Let h_next2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, (j plus 1) multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(h, (j plus 1) multiplied by 8, h_next2 plus c2)
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Force-positive pass. After the balanced carries above, each
    Note: limb sits in [-2^27, 2^27). Add 2^28 to any negative limb and
    Note: propagate a -1 borrow into the next-higher limb. A final
    Note: borrow at limb 15 means the value went below zero; since
    Note: 2^448 = 2^224 + 1 (mod p), we added 2^448 to V which equals
    Note: adding 2^224 + 1 mod p, so we subtract 1 from limb 0 and 1
    Note: from limb 8 to keep the residue invariant.
    Let g0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 0)
    Let g1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 8)
    Let g2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 16)
    Let g3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 24)
    Let g4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 32)
    Let g5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 40)
    Let g6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 48)
    Let g7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 56)
    Let g8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 64)
    Let g9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 72)
    Let g10 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 80)
    Let g11 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 88)
    Let g12 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 96)
    Let g13 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 104)
    Let g14 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 112)
    Let g15 be Memory.memory_get_int64(h, 120)

    Let bb0 be (g0 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g0 to g0 plus (bb0 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g1 to g1 minus bb0
    Let bb1 be (g1 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g1 to g1 plus (bb1 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g2 to g2 minus bb1
    Let bb2 be (g2 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g2 to g2 plus (bb2 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g3 to g3 minus bb2
    Let bb3 be (g3 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g3 to g3 plus (bb3 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g4 to g4 minus bb3
    Let bb4 be (g4 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g4 to g4 plus (bb4 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g5 to g5 minus bb4
    Let bb5 be (g5 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g5 to g5 plus (bb5 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g6 to g6 minus bb5
    Let bb6 be (g6 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g6 to g6 plus (bb6 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g7 to g7 minus bb6
    Let bb7 be (g7 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g7 to g7 plus (bb7 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g8 to g8 minus bb7
    Let bb8 be (g8 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g8 to g8 plus (bb8 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g9 to g9 minus bb8
    Let bb9 be (g9 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g9 to g9 plus (bb9 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g10 to g10 minus bb9
    Let bb10 be (g10 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g10 to g10 plus (bb10 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g11 to g11 minus bb10
    Let bb11 be (g11 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g11 to g11 plus (bb11 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g12 to g12 minus bb11
    Let bb12 be (g12 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g12 to g12 plus (bb12 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g13 to g13 minus bb12
    Let bb13 be (g13 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g13 to g13 plus (bb13 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g14 to g14 minus bb13
    Let bb14 be (g14 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g14 to g14 plus (bb14 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g15 to g15 minus bb14
    Let bb15 be (g15 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g15 to g15 plus (bb15 multiplied by 268435456)

    Note: Goldilocks wrap-back of the final borrow: subtract 1 from
    Note: limb 0 and limb 8 (which is at radix offset 28*8 = 224 bits).
    Set g0 to g0 minus bb15
    Set g8 to g8 minus bb15

    Note: Second force-positive sweep to clean up any negative residue
    Note: introduced by the bb15 compensation. After the first sweep,
    Note: limbs were in [0, 2^28); subtracting bb15 (0 or 1) from limbs
    Note: 0 and 8 leaves them in [-1, 2^28-1]. A linear borrow
    Note: propagation absorbs the borrow at the first non-zero limb
    Note: encountered upward. The Goldilocks fold guarantee from stage 1
    Note: ensures the integer value is in [0, 2^448), so this sweep does
    Note: not need its own wrap-back: no cb15 ever fires (proven by the
    Note: bound that after stage 1 the represented integer is in
    Note: [0, 2^448 - 1] and the bb15 wrap-back subtracts at most
    Note: 2^224 + 1, keeping the integer non-negative).
    Let cb0 be (g0 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g0 to g0 plus (cb0 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g1 to g1 minus cb0
    Let cb1 be (g1 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g1 to g1 plus (cb1 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g2 to g2 minus cb1
    Let cb2 be (g2 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g2 to g2 plus (cb2 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g3 to g3 minus cb2
    Let cb3 be (g3 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g3 to g3 plus (cb3 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g4 to g4 minus cb3
    Let cb4 be (g4 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g4 to g4 plus (cb4 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g5 to g5 minus cb4
    Let cb5 be (g5 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g5 to g5 plus (cb5 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g6 to g6 minus cb5
    Let cb6 be (g6 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g6 to g6 plus (cb6 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g7 to g7 minus cb6
    Let cb7 be (g7 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g7 to g7 plus (cb7 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g8 to g8 minus cb7
    Let cb8 be (g8 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g8 to g8 plus (cb8 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g9 to g9 minus cb8
    Let cb9 be (g9 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g9 to g9 plus (cb9 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g10 to g10 minus cb9
    Let cb10 be (g10 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g10 to g10 plus (cb10 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g11 to g11 minus cb10
    Let cb11 be (g11 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g11 to g11 plus (cb11 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g12 to g12 minus cb11
    Let cb12 be (g12 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g12 to g12 plus (cb12 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g13 to g13 minus cb12
    Let cb13 be (g13 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g13 to g13 plus (cb13 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g14 to g14 minus cb13
    Let cb14 be (g14 shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Set g14 to g14 plus (cb14 multiplied by 268435456)
    Set g15 to g15 minus cb14

    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 0, g0)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 8, g1)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 16, g2)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 24, g3)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 32, g4)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 40, g5)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 48, g6)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 56, g7)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 64, g8)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 72, g9)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 80, g10)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 88, g11)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 96, g12)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 104, g13)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 112, g14)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(h, 120, g15)

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 4: Multiplication (schoolbook + Goldilocks reduction)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe448_mul" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Schoolbook multiplication of two 16-limb radix-2^28 elements, then
    reduce via 2^448 = 2^224 + 1 (Goldilocks).

    Step 1 computes the 31 cross-product sums r[0..30]:
      r[k] = sum_{i+j=k} a_i * b_j  for k in [0, 30]

    Step 2 folds limbs r[16..30] back into r[0..15] using:
      r[i]   += r[i+16] * 1        (contribution from 2^448 reducing to 1)
      r[i+8] += r[i+16] * 1        (contribution from 2^448 reducing to 2^224)
    so each high-index limb r[i+16] doubles into limbs i and i+8 of the
    reduced result. The bounded ranges of inputs keep this within 64-bit.

    The schedule below merges the two steps: r[16+i] is computed but
    not stored, and its value is directly folded into r[i] and r[i+8]
    via additions to the running sums.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Loads all 16 limbs of a and b. Computes each output limb r[i] for
    i in [0, 15] by:
      r[i] = sum_{j+k=i, 0<=j,k<16} a_j * b_k +
             sum_{j+k=i+16, 0<=j,k<16} a_j * b_k +
             sum_{j+k=i+8, 0<=j,k<16, i+8 in [16,30]} a_j * b_k (only if i < 8 too)
    Wait: the wrap rule is r[i] += r[i+16] (mod position-aware). For
    i+16 in [16, 30], r[i+16] is the limb at position i+16; its
    Goldilocks contribution is +1 to limb i and +1 to limb i+8 (with
    i+8 itself in [8, 22], folding back through 16 as well if i+8 >= 16).

    Specifically, every "high" limb at position k in [16, 30] contributes:
      - to limb (k - 16)        (the +1 part)
      - to limb (k - 8)         (the +2^224 part)
        - if k - 8 >= 16 (k >= 24), this itself is a high limb that
          needs further folding: k-8 in [16, 22], contributing to
          (k-24) and (k-16). Since we are computing r[i] for i in
          [0, 15] only, we expand these folds inline.

    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    256 multiplications + ~256 additions + 16 carries. The wrap folding
    adds zero extra multiplications, only additions.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: fixed sequence of arithmetic.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let a0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 0)
    Let a1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 8)
    Let a2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 16)
    Let a3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 24)
    Let a4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 32)
    Let a5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 40)
    Let a6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 48)
    Let a7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 56)
    Let a8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 64)
    Let a9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 72)
    Let a10 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 80)
    Let a11 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 88)
    Let a12 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 96)
    Let a13 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 104)
    Let a14 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 112)
    Let a15 be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, 120)

    Let b0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 0)
    Let b1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 8)
    Let b2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 16)
    Let b3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 24)
    Let b4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 32)
    Let b5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 40)
    Let b6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 48)
    Let b7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 56)
    Let b8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 64)
    Let b9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 72)
    Let b10 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 80)
    Let b11 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 88)
    Let b12 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 96)
    Let b13 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 104)
    Let b14 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 112)
    Let b15 be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, 120)

    Note: Compute the 31 raw cross-sum limbs r0..r30 of the 16x16 product.
    Note: We accumulate into 31 64-bit Integer locals.

    Let r0 be a0 multiplied by b0
    Let r1 be a0 multiplied by b1
    Set r1 to r1 plus a1 multiplied by b0
    Let r2 be a0 multiplied by b2
    Set r2 to r2 plus a1 multiplied by b1
    Set r2 to r2 plus a2 multiplied by b0
    Let r3 be a0 multiplied by b3
    Set r3 to r3 plus a1 multiplied by b2
    Set r3 to r3 plus a2 multiplied by b1
    Set r3 to r3 plus a3 multiplied by b0
    Let r4 be a0 multiplied by b4
    Set r4 to r4 plus a1 multiplied by b3
    Set r4 to r4 plus a2 multiplied by b2
    Set r4 to r4 plus a3 multiplied by b1
    Set r4 to r4 plus a4 multiplied by b0
    Let r5 be a0 multiplied by b5
    Set r5 to r5 plus a1 multiplied by b4
    Set r5 to r5 plus a2 multiplied by b3
    Set r5 to r5 plus a3 multiplied by b2
    Set r5 to r5 plus a4 multiplied by b1
    Set r5 to r5 plus a5 multiplied by b0
    Let r6 be a0 multiplied by b6
    Set r6 to r6 plus a1 multiplied by b5
    Set r6 to r6 plus a2 multiplied by b4
    Set r6 to r6 plus a3 multiplied by b3
    Set r6 to r6 plus a4 multiplied by b2
    Set r6 to r6 plus a5 multiplied by b1
    Set r6 to r6 plus a6 multiplied by b0
    Let r7 be a0 multiplied by b7
    Set r7 to r7 plus a1 multiplied by b6
    Set r7 to r7 plus a2 multiplied by b5
    Set r7 to r7 plus a3 multiplied by b4
    Set r7 to r7 plus a4 multiplied by b3
    Set r7 to r7 plus a5 multiplied by b2
    Set r7 to r7 plus a6 multiplied by b1
    Set r7 to r7 plus a7 multiplied by b0
    Let r8 be a0 multiplied by b8
    Set r8 to r8 plus a1 multiplied by b7
    Set r8 to r8 plus a2 multiplied by b6
    Set r8 to r8 plus a3 multiplied by b5
    Set r8 to r8 plus a4 multiplied by b4
    Set r8 to r8 plus a5 multiplied by b3
    Set r8 to r8 plus a6 multiplied by b2
    Set r8 to r8 plus a7 multiplied by b1
    Set r8 to r8 plus a8 multiplied by b0
    Let r9 be a0 multiplied by b9
    Set r9 to r9 plus a1 multiplied by b8
    Set r9 to r9 plus a2 multiplied by b7
    Set r9 to r9 plus a3 multiplied by b6
    Set r9 to r9 plus a4 multiplied by b5
    Set r9 to r9 plus a5 multiplied by b4
    Set r9 to r9 plus a6 multiplied by b3
    Set r9 to r9 plus a7 multiplied by b2
    Set r9 to r9 plus a8 multiplied by b1
    Set r9 to r9 plus a9 multiplied by b0
    Let r10 be a0 multiplied by b10
    Set r10 to r10 plus a1 multiplied by b9
    Set r10 to r10 plus a2 multiplied by b8
    Set r10 to r10 plus a3 multiplied by b7
    Set r10 to r10 plus a4 multiplied by b6
    Set r10 to r10 plus a5 multiplied by b5
    Set r10 to r10 plus a6 multiplied by b4
    Set r10 to r10 plus a7 multiplied by b3
    Set r10 to r10 plus a8 multiplied by b2
    Set r10 to r10 plus a9 multiplied by b1
    Set r10 to r10 plus a10 multiplied by b0
    Let r11 be a0 multiplied by b11
    Set r11 to r11 plus a1 multiplied by b10
    Set r11 to r11 plus a2 multiplied by b9
    Set r11 to r11 plus a3 multiplied by b8
    Set r11 to r11 plus a4 multiplied by b7
    Set r11 to r11 plus a5 multiplied by b6
    Set r11 to r11 plus a6 multiplied by b5
    Set r11 to r11 plus a7 multiplied by b4
    Set r11 to r11 plus a8 multiplied by b3
    Set r11 to r11 plus a9 multiplied by b2
    Set r11 to r11 plus a10 multiplied by b1
    Set r11 to r11 plus a11 multiplied by b0
    Let r12 be a0 multiplied by b12
    Set r12 to r12 plus a1 multiplied by b11
    Set r12 to r12 plus a2 multiplied by b10
