    Set r28 to r28 plus a15 multiplied by b13
    Let r29 be a14 multiplied by b15
    Set r29 to r29 plus a15 multiplied by b14
    Let r30 be a15 multiplied by b15

    Note: Goldilocks reduction. Each r[i+16] for i in [0..14] contributes
    Note: +1 to r[i] (the "+1" part of 2^448 = 2^224 + 1) and +1 to r[i+8]
    Note: (the "+2^224" part). Since (i+8) for i in [0..7] lands in
    Note: [8..15], that's a direct contribution. For i >= 8, (i+8) >= 16,
    Note: so the contribution itself folds: limb (i+8) is a high limb
    Note: that contributes to (i+8-16) = i-8 and (i+8-8) = i. We expand
    Note: the iterated folds inline.

    Note: First fold (r16..r30 -> r0..r22, then r17..r22 -> r1..r14, etc.)
    Note: But it's cleaner to just compute the final r0..r15 by
    Note: substituting both contributions of each high limb directly.

    Note: For each high index k in [16, 30]:
    Note:   contribution to limb (k - 16): always (single +1 from 2^448 = 2^224 + 1, the "+1" part)
    Note:   contribution to limb (k - 8) for k - 8 < 16: direct (the "+2^224" part)
    Note:                  for k - 8 >= 16: nested fold; (k-8) is a high limb of [16, 22]:
    Note:                    contributes to (k-8-16) = k-24 and (k-8-8) = k-16
    Note: Net direct contributions of r[k]:
    Note:   k=16:  to r[0]    (16-16) and r[8]    (16-8) -- both single hops
    Note:   k=17:  to r[1]    and r[9]
    Note:   ...
    Note:   k=23:  to r[7]    and r[15]
    Note:   k=24:  to r[8]    (24-16) and r[16]  -- (24-8); r[16] folds to r[0] and r[8]
    Note:                                            => net contributions r[0] (1) + r[8] (1 + 1) = r[8] doubled
    Note:   k=25:  to r[9]    and r[17] -> r[1] and r[9]
    Note:                                            => r[1] (1) + r[9] (1 + 1)
    Note:   ...
    Note:   k=30:  to r[14]   and r[22] -> r[6] and r[14]
    Note:                                            => r[6] (1) + r[14] (1 + 1)

    Note: After the iterated folds for k in [16..30]:
    Note:   r[i] for i in [0..6]: gets contributions from k=i+16 (single) and (if k=i+24<=30) k=i+24 (single via deeper fold)
    Note:   r[i] for i=7: gets contributions from k=23 (only)
    Note:   r[i] for i in [8..14]: gets contributions from k=i+8 (single, from deeper fold of k=i+16) AND
    Note:                          k=i+16 if i+16 < 31 ((only valid for i<=14: yes, since k=i+16 in [24..30] is valid))
    Note:                          plus contributions from k=i+8 (single direct hop from r[i+8]=high if i+8>=16)
    Note:   r[15]: contribution from r[23] (k=23 maps to r[15]) and nothing higher (r[31] doesn't exist)
    Note: Simpler restatement (the Goldilocks fold rule):
    Note:   r[i] += r[i+16] + r[i+8]_high   where the second term applies only if i+8 corresponds to a high index
    Note: Let's just directly compute the FINAL limbs using inline additions.

    Note: First-level fold: r[i+8] += r[i+16] for i in [0..6] (since r[i+16] for i in [0..6] are high limbs that contribute to position i+16-8=i+8).
    Note: But r[i+8] for i in [0..6] are LOW limbs (i+8 in [8..14]), so they remain final limbs.

    Note: Wait. Let me restate the Goldilocks reduction clearly.
    Note:   p = 2^448 - 2^224 - 1
    Note:   2^448 = 2^224 + 1 (mod p)
    Note: A multi-precision value h with limbs h[0..30] (radix 2^28) represents
    Note:   sum_{i=0..30} h[i] * 2^(28*i)
    Note: For i in [16..30], 2^(28*i) = 2^(28*i - 448) * 2^448 = 2^(28*i-448) * (2^224 + 1)
    Note:                            = 2^(28*(i-16)) * (2^224 + 1)
    Note:                            = 2^(28*(i-16)) + 2^(28*(i-16) + 224)
    Note:                            = 2^(28*(i-16)) + 2^(28*(i-16) + 28*8)
    Note:                            = 2^(28*(i-16)) + 2^(28*(i-8))
    Note: So h[i] for i in [16..30] contributes to limbs (i-16) and (i-8).

    Note: For i in [16..22], (i-8) is in [8..14] (still a low limb).
    Note: For i in [23..30], (i-8) is in [15..22]. (i-8 in [16..22] for i in [24..30])
    Note:    => i-8 itself is a "second-level high limb", and recursively contributes to (i-8-16) = i-24 and (i-8-8) = i-16.

    Note: So the FULL reduction rules:
    Note:   For i in [16..23]: r[i] adds to r[i-16] and r[i-8]
    Note:   For i in [24..30]: r[i] adds to r[i-16] (direct +1) and to r[i-8] (which is a high limb in [16..22]).
    Note:        That high contribution itself folds: into r[i-24] and r[i-16].
    Note:        So net additions from r[i]: +1 to r[i-16], +1 to r[i-16] (via second hop), +1 to r[i-24]
    Note:        = +2 to r[i-16] and +1 to r[i-24].
    Note:        Equivalently: r[i] contributes 2*r[i] to r[i-16] and 1*r[i] to r[i-24], for i in [24..30].

    Note: Note that r[i-8] for i in [16..23] (i.e., i-8 in [8..15]) is a normal low limb that just collects an addition.

    Note: Build final limbs:

    Note: Per the Goldilocks reduction analysis above:
    Note:   - r[i+16] for i in [0..7] contributes 1x to r[i] and 1x to r[i+8].
    Note:   - r[i+16] for i in [8..14] contributes 2x to r[i] and 1x to r[i-8].
    Note: Equivalently, r[k] for k in [16..23] adds 1x to f[k-16] and 1x to f[k-8];
    Note: r[k] for k in [24..30] adds 1x to f[k-24] and 2x to f[k-16].

    Let f0 be r0 plus r16 plus r24
    Let f1 be r1 plus r17 plus r25
    Let f2 be r2 plus r18 plus r26
    Let f3 be r3 plus r19 plus r27
    Let f4 be r4 plus r20 plus r28
    Let f5 be r5 plus r21 plus r29
    Let f6 be r6 plus r22 plus r30
    Let f7 be r7 plus r23
    Let f8 be r8 plus r16 plus 2 multiplied by r24
    Let f9 be r9 plus r17 plus 2 multiplied by r25
    Let f10 be r10 plus r18 plus 2 multiplied by r26
    Let f11 be r11 plus r19 plus 2 multiplied by r27
    Let f12 be r12 plus r20 plus 2 multiplied by r28
    Let f13 be r13 plus r21 plus 2 multiplied by r29
    Let f14 be r14 plus r22 plus 2 multiplied by r30
    Let f15 be r15 plus r23

    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 0, f0)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 8, f1)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 16, f2)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 24, f3)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 32, f4)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 40, f5)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 48, f6)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 56, f7)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 64, f8)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 72, f9)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 80, f10)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 88, f11)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 96, f12)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 104, f13)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 112, f14)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, 120, f15)

    proc fe448_carry with dest
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe448_sqr" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Squaring of a 16-limb field element. Delegated to fe448_mul with
    b = a for simplicity and shared correctness with the audited mul
    kernel. A specialized squaring schedule would halve the cross-
    product count at the cost of separate parity bookkeeping; we accept
    the constant-factor cost in exchange for a single reviewed kernel.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time, inherited from fe448_mul.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc fe448_mul with dest, a, a
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 5: Conditional swap and select
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe448_cswap" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, swap_bit as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time conditional swap of two field elements, branchless.
    Same XOR-with-mask pattern as fe25519_cswap, adapted to 16 limbs.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: same instruction sequence regardless of swap_bit.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mask be 0 minus swap_bit
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Let bi be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, i multiplied by 8)
        Let xored be ai bitwise_xor bi
        Let t be xored bitwise_and mask
        Memory.memory_set_qword(a, i multiplied by 8, ai bitwise_xor t)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(b, i multiplied by 8, bi bitwise_xor t)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe448_select" takes dest as Integer, a as Integer, b as Integer, condition as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time conditional move: dest := a if condition=1, else b.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mask be 0 minus condition
    Let not_mask be mask bitwise_xor (0 minus 1)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let ai be Memory.memory_get_int64(a, i multiplied by 8)
        Let bi be Memory.memory_get_int64(b, i multiplied by 8)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(dest, i multiplied by 8, (ai bitwise_and mask) bitwise_or (bi bitwise_and not_mask))
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 6: Pack/Unpack (field element <-> 56 bytes)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe448_unpack" takes fe as Integer, bytes56 as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Decodes a 56-byte little-endian buffer into a 16-limb radix-2^28
    field element. Each limb is 28 bits; pairs of consecutive limbs
    span 7 bytes. Specifically, limb i takes bits [28i, 28i+28). We
    extract 4 bytes per limb pair with a 4-bit shift mid-pair.

    Layout: 56 bytes = 8 groups of 7 bytes, each group encoding 2 limbs.
    For group g (g in [0, 8)):
      base = 7 * g
      limb (2g)   = byte[base+0] | byte[base+1]<<8 | byte[base+2]<<16 | (byte[base+3] & 0x0F)<<24
      limb (2g+1) = byte[base+3]>>4 | byte[base+4]<<4 | byte[base+5]<<12 | byte[base+6]<<20
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time byte unpacking; no branches.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let g be 0
    While g is less than 8:
        Let base be g multiplied by 7
        Let b0 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes56, base)
        Let b1 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes56, base plus 1)
        Let b2 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes56, base plus 2)
        Let b3 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes56, base plus 3)
        Let b4 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes56, base plus 4)
        Let b5 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes56, base plus 5)
        Let b6 be Memory.memory_get_byte(bytes56, base plus 6)

        Let lo_limb be b0
        Set lo_limb to lo_limb plus b1 multiplied by 256
        Set lo_limb to lo_limb plus b2 multiplied by 65536
        Set lo_limb to lo_limb plus (b3 bitwise_and 15) multiplied by 16777216

        Let hi_limb be b3 shifted right by 4
        Set hi_limb to hi_limb plus b4 multiplied by 16
        Set hi_limb to hi_limb plus b5 multiplied by 4096
        Set hi_limb to hi_limb plus b6 multiplied by 1048576

        Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, g multiplied by 16, lo_limb)
        Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, g multiplied by 16 plus 8, hi_limb)
        Set g to g plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe448_freeze" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Brings the field element to its unique canonical representative
    in [0, p). Two carry passes followed by a constant-time
    subtraction of p if the value is >= p.

    p = 2^448 - 2^224 - 1, so p in 16 limbs of 28-bit is:
      limbs 0..7:    2^28 - 1 except limb 0 = 2^28 - 1
      Actually: p = (2^224 - 1) * 2^224 + (2^224 - 1)
                  = (2^28-1)*2^(28*8) - (2^28-1)*... wait, let me restate.
      p in radix 2^28: 16 limbs where
        limb i = 2^28 - 1 = 268435455  for i in [0, 7]  (since these limbs sum to 2^224 - 1)
        limb 8 = 2^28 - 2 = 268435454                   (since limb 8 contributes the boundary)
        limb i = 2^28 - 1 = 268435455  for i in [9, 15] (sum to (2^224 - 1) * 2^224)
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc fe448_carry with fe
    proc fe448_carry with fe
    proc fe448_carry with fe

    Note: Force-positive: ensure each limb is in [0, 2^28). For each
    Note: negative limb h_i, add 2^28 and borrow 1 from h_{i+1}. Any
    Note: final borrow at limb 15 corresponds to subtracting 2^448 from V;
    Note: since 2^448 = 2^224 + 1 (mod p), the borrow propagates as:
    Note:   subtract 1 from limb 0 and 1 from limb 8.
    Let g0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 0)
    Let g1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 8)
    Let g2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 16)
    Let g3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 24)
    Let g4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 32)
    Let g5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 40)
    Let g6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 48)
    Let g7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 56)
    Let g8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 64)
    Let g9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 72)
    Let g10 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 80)
    Let g11 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 88)
    Let g12 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 96)
    Let g13 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 104)
    Let g14 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 112)
    Let g15 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 120)

    Let bb be 0
    If g0 is less than 0:
        Set g0 to g0 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g1 to g1 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g1 is less than 0:
        Set g1 to g1 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g2 to g2 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g2 is less than 0:
        Set g2 to g2 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g3 to g3 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g3 is less than 0:
        Set g3 to g3 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g4 to g4 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g4 is less than 0:
        Set g4 to g4 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g5 to g5 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g5 is less than 0:
        Set g5 to g5 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g6 to g6 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g6 is less than 0:
        Set g6 to g6 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g7 to g7 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g7 is less than 0:
        Set g7 to g7 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g8 to g8 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g8 is less than 0:
        Set g8 to g8 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g9 to g9 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g9 is less than 0:
        Set g9 to g9 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g10 to g10 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g10 is less than 0:
        Set g10 to g10 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g11 to g11 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g11 is less than 0:
        Set g11 to g11 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g12 to g12 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g12 is less than 0:
        Set g12 to g12 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g13 to g13 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g13 is less than 0:
        Set g13 to g13 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g14 to g14 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g14 is less than 0:
        Set g14 to g14 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If
    Set g15 to g15 minus bb
    Set bb to 0
    If g15 is less than 0:
        Set g15 to g15 plus 268435456
        Set bb to 1
    End If

    Note: Final borrow at limb 15 means V was < 0. We added 2^448 to V.
    Note: Since 2^448 = 2^224 + 1 mod p (because p = 2^448 - 2^224 - 1),
    Note: V (mod p) increased by (2^224 + 1). Decrement: subtract 1 from
    Note: limb 0 and 1 from limb 8 (which is at offset 224 = 28*8).
    Set g0 to g0 minus bb
    Set g8 to g8 minus bb

    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 0, g0)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 8, g1)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 16, g2)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 24, g3)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 32, g4)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 40, g5)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 48, g6)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 56, g7)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 64, g8)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 72, g9)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 80, g10)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 88, g11)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 96, g12)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 104, g13)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 112, g14)
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 120, g15)

    Note: Compute t = h - p with borrow.
    Let h0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 0)
    Let h1 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 8)
    Let h2 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 16)
    Let h3 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 24)
    Let h4 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 32)
    Let h5 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 40)
    Let h6 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 48)
    Let h7 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 56)
    Let h8 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 64)
    Let h9 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 72)
    Let h10 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 80)
    Let h11 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 88)
    Let h12 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 96)
    Let h13 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 104)
    Let h14 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 112)
    Let h15 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 120)

    Let mask be 268435455

    Note: Subtract p from h, limb by limb with borrow propagation.
    Note: Use signed Integer arithmetic; the borrow is captured as
    Note: the high bit of the (signed) difference.

    Let t0 be h0 minus 268435455
    Let borrow be t0 shifted right by 28
    Note: borrow is -1 if t0 < 0, 0 otherwise.
    Set t0 to t0 bitwise_and mask

    Let t1 be h1 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t1 shifted right by 28
    Set t1 to t1 bitwise_and mask

    Let t2 be h2 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t2 shifted right by 28
    Set t2 to t2 bitwise_and mask

    Let t3 be h3 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t3 shifted right by 28
    Set t3 to t3 bitwise_and mask

    Let t4 be h4 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t4 shifted right by 28
    Set t4 to t4 bitwise_and mask

    Let t5 be h5 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t5 shifted right by 28
    Set t5 to t5 bitwise_and mask

    Let t6 be h6 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t6 shifted right by 28
    Set t6 to t6 bitwise_and mask

    Let t7 be h7 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t7 shifted right by 28
    Set t7 to t7 bitwise_and mask

    Let t8 be h8 minus 268435454 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t8 shifted right by 28
    Set t8 to t8 bitwise_and mask

    Let t9 be h9 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t9 shifted right by 28
    Set t9 to t9 bitwise_and mask

    Let t10 be h10 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t10 shifted right by 28
    Set t10 to t10 bitwise_and mask

    Let t11 be h11 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t11 shifted right by 28
    Set t11 to t11 bitwise_and mask

    Let t12 be h12 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t12 shifted right by 28
    Set t12 to t12 bitwise_and mask

    Let t13 be h13 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t13 shifted right by 28
    Set t13 to t13 bitwise_and mask

    Let t14 be h14 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Set borrow to t14 shifted right by 28
    Set t14 to t14 bitwise_and mask

    Let t15 be h15 minus 268435455 plus borrow
    Let final_borrow be t15 shifted right by 28
    Set t15 to t15 bitwise_and mask

    Note: final_borrow == 0 means h - p >= 0 (h was >= p), so use t.
    Note: final_borrow == -1 means h - p < 0 (h < p), so use h.
    Note: select_mask: all-ones if h>=p (use t), all-zeros if h<p (use h).
    Let use_t_mask be final_borrow plus 1
    Note: final_borrow is 0 or -1; +1 gives 1 or 0. Build to all-ones via negation.
    Let select_mask be 0 minus use_t_mask
    Let not_select_mask be select_mask bitwise_xor (0 minus 1)

    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 0, (t0 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h0 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 8, (t1 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h1 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 16, (t2 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h2 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 24, (t3 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h3 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 32, (t4 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h4 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 40, (t5 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h5 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 48, (t6 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h6 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 56, (t7 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h7 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 64, (t8 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h8 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 72, (t9 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h9 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 80, (t10 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h10 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 88, (t11 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h11 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 96, (t12 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h12 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 104, (t13 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h13 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 112, (t14 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h14 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Memory.memory_set_qword(fe, 120, (t15 bitwise_and select_mask) bitwise_or (h15 bitwise_and not_select_mask))
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "fe448_pack" takes fe as Integer, bytes56_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Packs a field element to 56 bytes little-endian. Each pair of
    limbs (28-bit + 28-bit) packs into 7 bytes.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc fe448_freeze with fe

    Let g be 0
    While g is less than 8:
        Let base be g multiplied by 7
        Let lo_limb be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, g multiplied by 16)
        Let hi_limb be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, g multiplied by 16 plus 8)

        Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes56_out, base, lo_limb bitwise_and 255)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes56_out, base plus 1, (lo_limb shifted right by 8) bitwise_and 255)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes56_out, base plus 2, (lo_limb shifted right by 16) bitwise_and 255)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes56_out, base plus 3, ((lo_limb shifted right by 24) bitwise_or (hi_limb multiplied by 16)) bitwise_and 255)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes56_out, base plus 4, (hi_limb shifted right by 4) bitwise_and 255)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes56_out, base plus 5, (hi_limb shifted right by 12) bitwise_and 255)
        Memory.memory_set_byte(bytes56_out, base plus 6, (hi_limb shifted right by 20) bitwise_and 255)
        Set g to g plus 1
    End While
    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 7: Equality and zero tests
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe448_is_zero" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Constant-time zero test (mod p). Freezes the input and ORs all
    limbs together.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope

    proc fe448_freeze with fe
    Let or_acc be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 16:
        Let limb be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, i multiplied by 8)
        Set or_acc to or_acc bitwise_or limb
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Let neg_or be 0 minus or_acc
    Let or_or_neg be or_acc bitwise_or neg_or
    Let nonzero_bit be (or_or_neg shifted right by 63) bitwise_and 1
    Return 1 minus nonzero_bit
End Process

Process called "fe448_is_negative" takes fe as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Returns the LSB of the canonical representative. Used for Ed448
    point encoding (the sign of x is encoded in a separate byte).
    @End Reasoning

    proc fe448_freeze with fe
    Let h0 be Memory.memory_get_int64(fe, 0)
    Return h0 bitwise_and 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: SECTION 8: Inversion via Fermat (a^(p-2) mod p)
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fe448_inv" takes arena as Integer, dest as Integer, a as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Computes a^-1 (mod p) via Fermat: a^(p-2) where p = 2^448 - 2^224 - 1.
      p - 2 = 2^448 - 2^224 - 3

    Strategy (addition chain optimized for Goldilocks):
      Let t = a^(2^223 - 1)  (Frobenius-style sub-chain)
      Compute step by step using consecutive squarings and a few
      multiplications:
        a^2, a^3, a^(2^2-1), a^(2^4-1), a^(2^8-1), a^(2^16-1),
        a^(2^32-1), a^(2^64-1), a^(2^128-1), a^(2^224-1)
      Final assembly:
        t = (a^(2^224 - 1))^2 * a              = a^(2^225 - 1)
        u = t^(2^223) * (a^(2^223 - 1))         = a^(2^448 - 2^224 - 1) ... etc

    The chain below builds a^(2^448 - 2^224 - 3) directly:
      r = a^(2^448 - 2^224 - 1) / a^2
        = a^((2^448 - 2^224 - 1) - 2)
        = a^(p - 2)

    Reference: Hamburg "Ed448-Goldilocks" appendix, addition chain
    similar to ed448-donna's invert function.
    @End Reasoning

    @Security_Scope
    Constant-time: fixed chain length and fixed sequence of squarings
    and multiplications.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let t1 be proc fe448_alloc with arena
    Let t2 be proc fe448_alloc with arena
    Let t3 be proc fe448_alloc with arena
    If t1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If t3 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: t1 = a^2
    proc fe448_sqr with t1, a
    Note: t1 = a^3 = a^2 * a
    proc fe448_mul with t1, t1, a
    Note: t1 = a^(2^2 - 1) = a^3   (same value)
    Note: Square once: t2 = a^(2^2) = a^4
    proc fe448_sqr with t2, t1
    Note: t1 = a^(2^3 - 1) = t1^2 * a = a^4 * a = a^5? Actually 2^3-1=7.
    Note: Use careful Brauer chain:

    Note: Standard sliding-window chain for Goldilocks inversion (works
    Note: regardless of cleverness):
    Note:   r = a; loop e = p - 2 = bit-by-bit; for each bit b from MSB
    Note:   to LSB: r = r^2; if b: r *= a.
    Note: 448 squarings + ~224 multiplications. Slow but constant-time.

    Note: Implement the straightforward binary chain using p_minus_2 as
    Note: a bit sequence read from a fixed byte buffer.

    proc fe448_set_one with t1
    Let p_m2_bytes be Arena.arena_allocate(arena, 56)
    If p_m2_bytes is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Note: p - 2 in 56 bytes little-endian:
    Note: p - 2 = 2^448 - 2^224 - 3
    Note:       = 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFE
    Note:         FFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFE
    Note: Bytes (LE): byte 0 = 0xFD (=253), bytes 1..27 = 0xFF, byte 28 = 0xFE,
    Note:            bytes 29..55 = 0xFF.
    Memory.memory_set_byte(p_m2_bytes, 0, 253)
    Let pi be 1
    While pi is less than 28:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(p_m2_bytes, pi, 255)
        Set pi to pi plus 1
    End While
    Memory.memory_set_byte(p_m2_bytes, 28, 254)
    Set pi to 29
    While pi is less than 56:
        Memory.memory_set_byte(p_m2_bytes, pi, 255)
        Set pi to pi plus 1
    End While

    Note: Square-and-multiply from MSB. Loop over bit_index from 447 down to 0.
    Let bit_index be 447
    While bit_index is greater than 0 minus 1:
        proc fe448_sqr with t1, t1
        Let byte_index be bit_index shifted right by 3
        Let bit_in_byte be bit_index bitwise_and 7
        Let byte_val be Memory.memory_get_byte(p_m2_bytes, byte_index)
        Let bit_val be (byte_val shifted right by bit_in_byte) bitwise_and 1
        Note: If bit set, multiply t1 by a; otherwise keep t1 (constant-time select).
        proc fe448_mul with t2, t1, a
        proc fe448_select with t1, t2, t1, bit_val
        Set bit_index to bit_index minus 1
    End While

    proc fe448_copy with dest, t1
    Return 1
End Process
